\begin_layout Title
How to compute the value of parameter U in the advection term
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Question
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We want to better motivate physically the values of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 used in the turbulence map (eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Pierrehumbert_map"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "pierrehumbert_tracer_1994"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "ngan_scalar_2011"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{cases}
x(t+\tau) & =x'(t)+\frac{U\tau}{c}\cos\left(ky'(t)+\phi(t)\right)\\
y(t+\tau) & =y'(t)+\frac{U\tau}{c}\cos\left(kz'(t)+\theta(t)\right)\\
z(t+\tau) & =z'(t)+\frac{U\tau}{c}\cos\left(kx(t+\tau)+\psi(t)\right)
\end{cases}\label{eq:Pierrehumbert_map}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $x'(t)$
\end_inset

 is the result of the displacement by diffusion from 
\begin_inset Formula $x(t)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the following, we define 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 the speed of the flow (in the referential of the small, 1cm length moving
 fluid element) as the sum of the components of the displacement vector,
 divided by the duration of a timestep, i.e.:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{array}{ccc}
V & = & \frac{1}{\tau}\sqrt{\left(x(t+\tau)-x'(t)\right)^{2}+\left(y(t+\tau)-y'(t)\right)^{2}+\left(z(t+\tau)-z'(t)\right)^{2}}\\
\left\langle V\right\rangle  & = & \frac{1}{\tau}\sqrt{\left\langle \left(\frac{U}{c}\right)^{2}\cos^{2}\left(ky'(t)+\phi(t)\right)+\left(\frac{U}{c}\right)^{2}\cos^{2}\left(kz'(t)+\theta(t)\right)+\left(\frac{U}{c}\right)^{2}\cos^{2}\left(kx(t+\tau)+\psi(t)\right)\right\rangle }
\end{array}\label{eq:v_whole_formula}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From this formula, we may be able to get 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

.
 Intuitively, we thought that we should have 
\begin_inset Formula $U=V_{\textmd{max}}$
\end_inset

 (maximal speed) or 
\begin_inset Formula $U=<V>$
\end_inset

 (effective speed).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Obtaining flow speed V from the Reynolds number
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are working at the Kolmogorov scale, i.e.
 the Reynolds number 
\begin_inset Formula $Re\approx1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The usual formulation of the Reynolds number is :
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Re=\frac{VL_{c}}{\nu}\label{eq:re_first}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is the velocity of the flow (m.s
\begin_inset Formula $^{-1}$
\end_inset

), 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{c}$
\end_inset

 is a characteristic linear dimension (m) and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu=10^{-6}$
\end_inset

 m
\begin_inset Formula $^{2}$
\end_inset

.s
\begin_inset Formula $^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is the kinematic viscosity of the fluid.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We first define 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{c}$
\end_inset

 as the dimension of the cube corresponding to the Kolmogorov scale.
 In the ocean, this corresponds to scales between 0.1 and 1 cm 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "barton_impact_2014"
literal "false"

