\begin_layout Standard

\change_inserted -2100369821 1636539449
There are two types of particles here, corresponding to two reference frames,
 and I think we have been doing it wrong:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\change_inserted -2100369821 1636540019
we model a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

particle of water
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of 1cm
\begin_inset Formula $^{3}$
\end_inset

 (or an aggregation of such particles), which we will call a volume of water
 hereafter in order to avoid any confusion.
 The size of this volume of water corresponds to the size of the smallest
 possible eddy, istelf enclosed inside larger eddies.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\change_inserted -2100369821 1636539850
we model a phytoplankton particle within the volume of water.
 This is the phytoplankton particle whose speed we want to look at.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\change_inserted -2100369821 1636540038
Applying the Reynolds number to the volume of water as we do in Section
 S1 only tells us the speed of the volume (most likely in the largest eddy's
 reference frame not in the terrestrial reference frame, but I am not completely
 positive about it).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\change_inserted -2100369821 1636541424
However, 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is actually the speed of the particle within the particle of water.
 In this case, we only want the difference of speeds between the speed of
 the volume and the speed of the particle.
 As written in Kiorboe (2008), 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

a solid body in a velocity gradient cannot travel with the same velocity
 as the ambient fluid, it will experience a velocity difference [in much
 the same way as a swimming or sinking plankter]
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 The corresponding velocity difference can be computed as follow
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\change_inserted -2100369821 1636540965
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
U_{turb}=\gamma r_{0}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 is the shear rate.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\change_inserted -2100369821 1636540980
